        <main>
            <h1>Major Findings</h1>
            <p>During the exploratory data analysis (EDA) phase, we observed that no single economic indicator
                follows a consistent pattern before every recession. Each historical U.S. recession was triggered by
                different factors — from oil shocks and aggressive Fed tightening to housing bubbles and a global
                pandemic. Because of this, rather than looking for one universal warning sign, we compared the current
                data (April 2024 – March 2026) for each of the six indicators against every pre-recession period across
                six time windows to determine which past recession today's economy most closely resembles.</p>
            <section>
                <h2>1. Analysis Findings</h2>
                <h3>1.1 Overall Recession Similarity Ranking</h3>
                <p>The two bar graphs below rank all eight recessions by their average similarity score across all
                    <strong>six indicators</strong> and all <strong>six time windows</strong>.
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Overall-Recession-similarity.png"
                        alt="Overall Recession Similarity Ranking">
                </figure>

                <p>Two recessions stand out as statistically notable matches to the current economic environment:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>2008</strong> is the clearest match to today, with the highest similarity in both
                        measures, followed by <strong>2020</strong> as the second closest.</li>
                    <li>Most other recessions show only moderate similarity (scores mostly between 40–59), meaning
                        today’s conditions are not strongly aligned with them.</li>
                    <li>DTW scores are consistently higher than Spearman, suggesting the overall patterns/trends look
                        similar, even if the exact relationships between indicators are weaker.</li>
                </ul>

                <br>
                <h3>1.2 Similarity by Time Window (averaged across all indicators)</h3>
                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/Major%20findings/average-across-indicators.png" alt="Similarity by Time Window">
                </figure>
                <p>The current economic trend most <strong>closely</strong> resembles the <strong>2008 Great
                        Recession</strong> pre-recession period,
                    consistently scoring the highest similarity across nearly all look-back windows — peaking at 79.0 at
                    the 1-year mark. The <strong>2020 COVID Pandemic</strong> and <strong>1981 High Interest
                        Rates</strong>
                    periods also show elevated
                    similarity, particularly at shorter and longer time windows respectively. Similarity scores are
                    generally weakest for the 1980 Volcker Inflation Fight, suggesting today's environment diverges most
                    from that era. The 1-year look-back window tends to produce the strongest signal across most
                    recessions, making it the most informative timeframe for comparison.</p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.3 Similarity by Economic Indicator (averaged across all time windows)</h3>
                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/Major%20findings/average-across-time-windows.png"
                        alt="Similarity by Economic Indicator">
                </figure>
                <p><strong>Gold</strong> and <strong>SP500</strong> are the strongest differentiating indicators, with
                    Gold showing
                    near-identical
                    behavior to both the <strong>2008 Great Recession</strong> (86.9) and <strong>2020 COVID
                        Pandemic</strong> (84.6). SP500 aligns
                    closely with the <strong>2008 recession</strong> (84.0) and <strong>1981 High Interest
                        Rates</strong> (82.4). Interest rates tell a
                    more mixed story — showing low similarity to stagflation-era recessions (29.3–30.2) but moderate
                    alignment elsewhere. Oil and VIX show the most variability, with Oil diverging significantly from
                    the <strong>1990 Gulf War shock</strong> (29.7) and VIX doing the same for that period (26.7).
                    Overall, the
                    indicator-level breakdown confirms that 2008 and 2020 are the dominant analogues, driven primarily
                    by gold and equity market behavior.</p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.5 1-Year Trend Comparison (current vs top 2 matching periods per indicator)</h3>
                <p>Across all six indicators, the current 2024–2026 trend traces patterns that closely mirror
                    pre-recession trajectories from past downturns:</p>

                <h4>1.5.1. Unemployment:</h4>
                <p><strong>Unemployment</strong> tracks the 2008 recession most closely (score: 78), with a rising
                    trend in recent months mirroring the pre-crisis buildup seen in both 2008 and 1969.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/Unemployment.png" alt="Trend Unemployment">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/Unemployment.png" alt="Trend Unemployment">
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h4>1.5.2. Interest rates:</h4>
                <p><strong>Interest rates</strong> are the standout signal — scoring 96 against the 2020 COVID
                    Pandemic and 91 against 2008, with a sharp decline from peak levels closely replicating both
                    pre-recession rate-cut cycles.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/Interest.png" alt="Trend Interest Rates">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/Interest.png" alt="Trend Interest Rates">
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h4>1.5.3. Oil prices:</h4>
                <p><strong>Oil prices</strong> show the weakest match overall (best score: 75 vs 2008), with
                    current prices remaining subdued and not replicating the sharp spikes seen historically.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/Oil.png" alt="Trend Oil Prices">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/Oil.png" alt="Trend Oil Prices">
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h4>1.5.4. SP500:</h4>
                <p><strong>SP500</strong> mirrors both the 1980 Volcker period and 2008 (both score 86), showing a
                    prolonged upward climb that historically preceded a sharp correction.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/SP500.png" alt="Trend SP500">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/SP500.png" alt="Trend SP500">
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h4>1.5.5. VIX:</h4>
                <p><strong>VIX</strong> aligns with the 2001 Dot-Com Bust (74), with a recent spike at the zero
                    mark suggesting rising market anxiety similar to the lead-up to that crash.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/VIX.png" alt="Trend VIX">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/VIX.png" alt="Trend VIX">
                    </figure>
                </div>

                <h4>1.5.6. Gold:</h4>
                <p><strong>Gold</strong> is the most alarming signal — scoring 92 against 2020 and 90 against 2008
                    — with a steep, sustained rise in the final months almost perfectly replicating both
                    pre-recession safe-haven surges.</p>

                <div class="content-grid">
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Spearman/Gold.png" alt="Trend Gold">
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/images/Major%20findings/DTW/Gold.png" alt="Trend Gold">
                    </figure>
                </div>
                <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Interest rates, gold, and equities collectively paint the most
                    consistent pre-recession picture, with the 2008 Great Recession emerging as the single strongest
                    historical analogue across the broadest set of indicators.</p>

